Picker, in San Francisco.  Mr. Reardon noted that investor-owned utility shareholders should be subject to the risks and rewards of portfolio management decisions so that their incentives are aligned with those of ratepayers. Mr. Reardon emphasized the need to extract maximum value from existing contracts, and pointed to the California Community Choice Association’s voluntary buy-down and auction proposals as effective methods to achieve this.

Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. Mr. Chaset expressed concern that no changes to the Proposed Decision (PD) or Alternate Proposed Decision (APD) had been issued to date in this proceeding. Mr. Chaset suggested that a hold be issued to delay the decision to give interested parties adequate time to respond, and that the Commission should consider allowing for a round of comments or another all-party meeting after any changes are released, given the significance of the issue and its impact on parties.

dc519652fc8e9936179080ae71268eb1.description: SUMMARY:  On October 1, 2018, Nora Sheriff, counsel, the California Large Energy Consumers Association (CLECA), spoke by phone with Rachel Peterson, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, and on October 3, 2018, Ms. Sheriff met with David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman-Aceves, and Yuliya Shmidt, advisor to Cmmr. Rechtschaffen, in two separate meetings in San Francisco, and spoke by phone with Forest Kaser, advisor to Cmmr. Picker. Ms. Sheriff stated that CLECA has bundled members, Direct Access members, and members who are now served by Community Choice Aggregators, as well as some members with onsite renewable generation to serve a portion of their load. Ms. Sheriff explained that with this membership, CLECA always tries to be as evenhanded as possible for purposes of how the different types of customers are treated. Ms. Sheriff told that CLECA strongly supports the Alternate Proposed Decision (APD), especially its treatment of legacy Utility Owned Generation costs.  Ms. Sheriff asked for the APD to be revised to explicitly reject the Joint Utilities’ proposal for a new, non-vintaged charge. Ms. Sheriff explained that substantial evidence in the proceeding weighs against adoption of the Joint Utilities’ proposal to change the power charge indifference adjustment allocator. Ms. Sheriff explained that if the Commission seeks consistency in allocation factors for bundled and departing customers, it should direct the filing of Rate Design Window applications on this narrow issue – which will give notice to other parties. With Mr. Gamson and Ms. Shmidt, Ms. Sheriff also noted CLECA’s recommendation that the APD be revised to allow for a de minimis valuation for unsold, excess resource adequacy and renewables portfolio standard resources that remain in the investor owned utilities’ portfolios, as opposed to a zero valuation.

Carla Peterman, in San Francisco. The Joint Utilities urged the Commission to adopt the APD with the modifications that the Joint Utilities have proposed, in order to ensure bundled service customer indifference. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

Solé, Deputy Director of Power Resources, San José Clean Energy (SJCE), met with Forest Kaser, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco.  Lori Mitchell, Director of Community Energy, SJCE, participated by telephone. Picker, and John Reynolds, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in two separate meetings in San Francisco. Suzy Hong, Deputy City Attorney, San Francisco City Attorney’s Office, the City and County of San Francisco (San Francisco) was also present. Ms. Hale described San Francisco’s Community Choice Aggregation (CCA) program, CleanPowerSF, and the potential impacts on CleanPowerSF of the Proposed Decision (PD) and the Alternate Proposed Decision (APD). Ms. Hale discussed how San Francisco believes that the PD provides a reasonable transition to the longer-term solutions proposed for Phase 2 of this proceeding. Ms. Hale explained concerns with the APD and its potential negative impacts on CleanPowerSF’s program. Ms. Hale highlighted how these impacts would hinder San Francisco’s ability to meet the City’s and the state’s environmental goals. Ms. Hale and Mr. Ramirez discussed San Francisco’s positions on the PD’s and APD’s treatment of issues regarding pre-2002 legacy utility-owned generation (UOG), the 10-year limit on cost recovery for post-2002 non-RPS UOG resources, the value for the capacity benchmark in the PCIA calculation, and a PCIA rate cap and collar. Ms. Hale and Mr. Ramirez noted San Franciso’s support of the positions of the California Community Choice Association on these issues. With respect to legacy UOG and the 10-year limit on cost recovery for post-2002 resources, Ms. Hale emphasized the need to provide incentive to investor-owned utilities (IOUs) to prudently manage their portfolios and resources. Ms. Hale questioned why IOUs should be allowed to recover from customers the uneconomic operating costs of resources owned by the IOUs.

Mr. Reardon noted that the rate tables PG&E provided on 8/31 contained errors which had not yet been addressed. Mr. Reardon highlighted the impact of a rising PCIA coupled with declining bundled rates on CCA competitiveness. SCP requested that the PD, not APD, be adopted. Rechtschaffen, in San Francisco. Cal PA expressed support for Commissioner Peterman’s Alternate Proposed Decision (APD) over the Proposed Decision (PD) and offered additional recommendations. Specifically, Ms. Halperin discussed aspects of the APD that are improvements over the PD. However, Cal PA opposes allowing Community Choice Aggregator and Direct Access providers to pre-pay their PCIA obligation. Referring to the greater rate impacts of the APD, Cal PA agreed to consider those rate impacts but suggested that the Commission’s decision should be driven by whichever methodology achieves indifference. Cal PA stated its general opposition to imposing a collar which is included in both the PD. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

49e6f52699b2ea6ae4f357150a70db2e.description: SUMMARY:  On September 5, 2018, Melissa Brandt, Senior Director of Public Affairs and Deputy General Counsel, Todd Edmister, Director of Regulatory Affairs and Deputy General Counsel and Nicolas Chaset, CEO, of East Bay Community Energy (EBCE), met with David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, and with James Ralph and Forest Kaser, advisors to Cmmr. Picker, in two separate meetings in San Francisco. At the second meeting, also present was Mitchell Shapson of the Legal Division. The discussion concerned the Power Charge Indifference Adjustment (PCIA) and EBCE’s perspective on the Proposed Decision (PD) and Alternate Proposed Decision (APD).  EBCE representatives pointed out that the utility narrative that bundled customers are bearing a significant cost shift under the current PCIA methodology is flawed; PG&E’s 2019 ERRA filing (A.18-06-001) shows bundled customer rates substantially declining and the PCIA for departed load customers going up significantly. EBCE representatives explained that the APD differs from the PD in material ways that would have catastrophic consequences for CCAs, and where the PD balanced changes that would benefit utilities with those that benefit CCAs, the APD makes changes that solely benefit utilities. EBCE representatives noted that both the PD and the APD create a cost shift onto CCAs by making the wrong changes to the capacity benchmark price. EBCE representatives explained that the APD will hinder achievement of the state’s energy goals. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

3b45dc428fdf8025d728c5076f6e2ebc.description: SUMMARY:  [JOINT] On September 5, 2018, Mary Lynch, Director of Wholesale Market Development for Constellation New Energy, and Greg Bass, Western Regulatory Director for Calpine Energy Solutions, on behalf of the Alliance for Retail Energy Markets (AReM); and Cynthia Clark of the University of California and, via telephone, Michael Rochman, Managing Director of the School Project for Utility Rate Reduction, on behalf of the Direct Access Customer Coalition (DACC), had a meeting with John Reynolds, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco. The AReM and DACC representatives discussed the impacts that each the Proposed Decision (PD) and Alternate Proposed Decision (APD) would have on Direct Access customers and Energy Service Providers, and stated a preference for the APD. In particular, the group discussed how the applicability of the legacy utility-owned generation costs for pre-2009 Vintage DA customers is already being addressed in A.16-04-018 et al and should be determined there; that the PD’s proposed treatment of legacy utility-owned generation costs in general might have unintended consequences; the PD’s revised market price benchmarks are not well defined, would be problematic, and that the use of the Renewable Energy Credit market index would be simpler, more accurate, more transparent and more predicable than the proposed RPS Adder. Further, the group expressed concern about the percent-based PCIA collar and discontinuation of the 10-year cost recovery rule that are proposed in the APD.

d5a2d8a013c79c5033f40072417791fd.description: [Joint] SUMMARY:  On June 28, 2018, Neal Reardon, Director of Regulatory Affairs, Sonoma Clean Power Authority (SCPA), had a telephonic conference with Joanna Gubman, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph. Nathaniel Malcolm, Policy Counsel, Marin Clean Energy (MCE), also participated in the communication. MCE and SCPA argued that the Joint Utilities’ Green Allocation Mechanism (GAM) violates statute by allocating products instead of costs to Community Choice Aggregators (CCA).  MCE and SCPA addressed the California Community Choice Association’s voluntary Staggered Portfolio Auction (SPA) as a way for all Load Serving Entities to acquire the RPS resources needed to serve their forecasted loads and meet, or voluntarily exceed RPS requirements. MCE and SCPA also noted that the GAM, unlike the SPA, would not provide CCAs the underlying energy associated with the allocated GAM Renewable Energy Credits. MCE and SCPA also indicated that they have no need for the Resource Adequacy (RA) allocations under the GAM. MCE and SCPA emphasized they are already positioned to meet their respective long-term Renewable Portfolio Standard (RPS) requirements. MCE and SCPA indicated that forcing MCE and SCPA to be excessively long on RPS would potentially bring Pacific Gas and Electric Company and Southern California Edison Company well under RPS compliance. MCE and SCPA challenged the Joint Utilities’ claims that the GAM is immediately implementable. Written materials (attached to the notice), sent via electronic mail in advance of the meeting on the same day, were used.

Mr. Perry explained that this model is based upon the successful allocation and auction procedure adopted by the Commission. Mr. Day and Mr. Perry explained that the VAAC auction would fix the cost of the winning bidder's portion of a generation pool, and at the same time fix the remaining PCIA costs associated with that resource. Mr. Day and Mr. Perry indicated that the Commission should combine useful recommendations from several parties in order to produce a comprehensive solution in the proceeding, including implementation of the VAAC allocation and auction procedures, together with the adoption of a residual PCIA recovery charge much like the final stage of the utilities' Portfolio Monetization Mechanism. In addition, on June 22, 2018, Mr. Day provided by electronic mail a cite to the Commission decision which adopted the PG&E/CTA allocation and auction process. fa998b471885b48b60864869d3fa71bd.description: [JOINT] SUMMARY:  On April 30, 2018, Mary Lynch of Constellation NewEnergy and Scott Olson of Direct Energy, representatives from the Alliance for Retail Energy Markets (AReM), met with James Ralph, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco. Also present were Cynthia Clark of the University of California, George Waidelich of Albertsons and Chris Hendrix of Walmart representing Direct Access Customer Coalition (DACC), Mark Fulmer of MRW & Associates, consultant to AReM and DACC, and Dan Douglass, counsel to AReM and DACC, attended telephonically. Mr. Olson and Ms. Lynch explained that the allocation of Renewable Energy Credits and Resource Adequacy through the utilities’ GAM approach does not meet what other load-serving entities want and need. Mr. Fulmer described the elements of his testimony. Mr. Waidelich explained that DA customers desire energy cost stability and predictability and that the biggest impediment is the volatility and unpredictability of Power Charge Indifference Adjustment (PCIA). Mr. Waidelich recommended that the Commission should allow DA customers to pre-pay their PCIA obligation, based on a mutually acceptable forecast of that customer’s future PCIA obligation. Mr. Hendrix discussed the AReM/DACC proposal that the Commission should institute a cap on the PCIA. Mr. Fulmer clarified that there is already a “floor” in place and that adding a cap would create a “collar” where exposure of DA and bundled customers to volatility is more symmetric. Ms. Clark noted that DA customers in the current pre-2009 vintage tranche that have paid their stranded cost obligations should be permanently exempted from any PCIA or successor tariff.

6aebc5e8e313359c06f24ff7cb9edac7.description: SUMMARY:  On November 2, 2017, Gary Stern, Director, Energy Policy, Southern California Edison Company (SCE), met with Cmmrs. Picker, Guzman Aceves, Peterman, Randolph, and Rechtschaffen during the Rulemaking 16-02-007 All Party Meeting on the Proposed Integrated Resource Planning (IRP) in San Francisco. Additionally, SCE believes that James Ralph, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, Candace Morey, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, Rachel Peterson, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, and Jason Houck, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, were present for all or portions of the All Party Meeting. Dr. Stern discussed the importance of cross-sector decarbonization opportunities in meeting the state’s greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions reduction and air quality goals. Dr. Stern stated that transportation and building electrification are critical to achieving California’s GHG emissions reduction goals, and will also improve air quality, including in disadvantaged communities. Dr. Stern noted that the most significant contribution to air pollution in disadvantaged communities is transportation sources. Dr. Stern also discussed how the proposed IRP process may create disincentives for pursuing electrification unless electric sector and load-serving entity GHG emissions reduction targets are adjusted to account for increased load due to electrification.

Ms. Brandt expressed concern that the Energy Division RA Report that will be used to determine the capacity value in the PCIA benchmark does not reflect enough of the actual market transactions, nor are updates to the report frequent enough. 6d0ed527e5b55026cde0109fc5e3652b.description: SUMMARY:  On October 3, 2018, Ms. Evelyn Kahl, Counsel, and Ms. Beth Vaughan, Executive Director, of to California Community Choice Association (CalCCA), met David M. Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman-Aceves, in San Francisco. Ms. Kahl observed that the determination of “indifference” rests on the valuation of the utilities’ portfolios, since Public Utilities Code §366.2(g) requires that the Commission reduce the portfolio cost by “the value of any benefits that remain with bundled service customers.” Ms. Kahl explained that the Alternate Proposed Decision (APD) does not achieve indifference in valuing the bundled utility portfolios and, instead, shifts costs to departing load customers. Ms. Kahl noted that the APD’s attempt to equate the products in the utilities’ portfolios with the benchmark proxies produces a material cost shift to departing load customers. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

0a87301c55152c6fa4f22a2ff2fea9f1.description: SUMMARY:  On September 6, 2018, Jan Pepper, Chief Executive Officer, Joseph F. Wiedman, Director of Legislative and Regulatory Affairs, Dave Pine, President of the San Mateo County Board of Supervisors and Peninsula Clean Energy Authority (PCE) Board Member, and Jeremy Waen, Senior Regulatory Analyst, on behalf of PCE, the City and County of San Francisco (CCSF), and Sonoma Clean Power Authority (SCPA), met with Joanna Gubman, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, and David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Martha Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. James Hendry, Regulatory and Legislative Affairs, Power Enterprise for the San Francisco Public Utilities Commission (operator of CleanPowerSF), and Neal Reardon, Director of Regulatory Affairs for SCPA, also participated on behalf of CCSF and SCPA, respectively. Mr. Hendry attended the meeting in person and Mr. Reardon attended by phone. PCE, CCSF, and SCPA representatives discussed the Proposed Decision of Administrative Law Judge Roscow (PD) and the August 14, 2018 Alternate Proposed Decision of Commissioner Peterman (APD). Ms. Pepper stated that a reasonable approach based on the record is to set the PCIA at the level contemplated by the PD or even maintain the PCIA at the current level until the second phase of the PCIA proceeding is completed. Mr. Waen discussed his experience working on PCIA issues over the course of his work with CCAs. Mr. Wiedman discussed support in the record for setting the benchmarks in a more reasonable fashion than either the APD or PD currently does and how the record supports the PD’s approach to the PCIA. Mr. Pine discussed the strong support for PCE within San Mateo County. Mr. Reardon discussed the impacts of the PCIA to SCPA’s residential customers while also noting that the rate tables PG&E provided on 8/31 contained errors which had not yet been addressed. Mr. Hendry commented that the PD/APD’s proposed value for capacity not only represents the low-range of values identified in the record of the proceeding but also represents the low range of the environmental attributes of the generation. Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

Peterman, in San Francisco. Also present were Colin Cushnie, Vice President of Energy Procurement and Management of SCE; Brian Prusnek, Director of Regulatory Affairs, and Emily Shults, Vice President of Electric and Fuel Procurement, of San Diego Gas & Electric Company; Erik Jacobson, Director of Regulatory Affairs, and Fong Wan, Senior Vice President of Energy Policy and Procurement of Pacific Gas and Electric Company; Colin Cushnie, Vice President of Energy Procurement and Management of SCE (collectively called “Joint Utilities Representatives”).  Joint Utilities Representatives discussed three major issues: (1) The Proposed Decision’s (PD) current treatment of Utility-Owned Generation (UOG) and energy storage resources; (2) the PD’s current PCIA “cost cap;” and (3) the PD’s PCIA “true-up” mechanism. Joint Utilities discussed how the current PD – if not modified – does not ensure bundled service customer indifference, as required by California statute. Joint Utilities Representatives discussed how the current PCIA “cost cap” is unreasonable and not equitable for bundled service customers. Joint Utilities explained the historical ratemaking treatment of UOG resources. Joint Utilities Representatives emphasized the need for additional clarity in the PD for the PCIA “true-up” mechanism. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

Mr. Day and Mr. Vanbeek explained the Commercial Energy proposal entitled “Voluntary Allocation & Auction Clearinghouse” (VAAC), and the participants and methodology for conducting the allocation and then an auction of remaining utility Power Charge Indifference Adjustment (PCIA)-eligible resources. Mr. Day explained that this model is based upon the successful allocation and auction procedure adopted by the Commission. Mr. Day and Mr. Vanbeek indicated that the Commission should combine useful recommendations from several parties in order to produce a comprehensive solution in the proceeding, including implementation of the VAAC allocation and auction procedures, together with the adoption of a residual PCIA recovery charge much like the final stage of the utilities’ Portfolio Monetization Mechanism. Mr. Day and Mr. Vanbeek suggested that at the same time, the Commission should allow the parties to pursue initiatives that may take longer to complete.
